  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Royal Edict Declining the Second Petition for Resignation of Minister Lee
  author: Lee Cham
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To restore order and set right what is broken requires a man of generation-spanning talents. To discourse on the Way and govern the realm demands a minister who acts as Heaven's deputy. Thus does one man's choice to remain or depart bear upon the nation's survival or ruin.

    Your Excellency—whose will surpasses wind and frost, whose vital force draws from sun and mountain—have long served the royal house with merit, and in this day bestow upon the common people your virtue. You drove the northern tribes from our borders and scattered the Japanese pirates across our four frontiers. After the late king's passing, a usurper bearing the name Shin seized the throne, abandoning governance for hunting and wine, dealing death at will, committing great villainy. He even raised armies to threaten the Middle Kingdom. Yet you, discerning right from wrong, rallied the people to righteousness. Consulting with kinsmen and ministers alike, you deposed the false pretender and elevated my humble person. Thus was our nation's foundation, nearly toppled, restored to stability; our ancestral line, severed, wove together again. Measuring your merit and virtue, they shine across ages past and present. You should forever support our house and pass honor to generations unborn.

    But alas, petty men have worked their treachery in shadow. This fault lies with me alone, not with you. I bear deep regret and now prepare to punish these schemers. Yet you have submitted a memorial requesting to resign from office. Though your deliberation runs deep, my hope is altogether different. Head and limbs form one body—can I forget the oath sworn beneath mountain and river? Trouble yourself no further with resignation. Return at once to your post. Your petition cannot be granted. Therefore this edict is issued. See that you understand.
  footnotes:
    - '山河帶礪 (Mountain and River Bound with Stone): A classical Chinese oath formula signifying eternal loyalty and unchanging bonds—here the king invokes the immutable nature of his covenant with his minister.'
    - '反正 (Reflecting Right): A euphemistic term for the successful coup d''état that brought the current king to power.'
    - '納氏/辛氏: References to historical enemies and the usurper respectively—specific historical context that anchors this edicted reply within a particular political moment.'
